.TH NP-UDP 4 "@PACKAGE_DATE@" "@PACKAGE@-@VERSION@" "@PACKAGE_TITLE@ Devices"
.\"
.\"
.SH NAME
.B np_udp
\- STREAMS User Datagram Protocol (UDP) Driver
.\"
.\"
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
.B #include <sys/socket.h>
.br
.B #include <netinet/ip.h>
.br
.B #include <netinet/udp.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/npi.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/npi_ip.h>
.br
.B #include <sys/npi_udp.h>
.HP 12
.BI "int " udp_stream " = open(" udp_device ", " oflag );
.\"
.\"
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The
.B NPI-UDP
pseudo-device
driver provides an interface between
.I STREAMS
drivers and the Linux UDP subsystem.  It presents an
.BR npi (7)
Network Provider Interface 
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
to
.I STREAMS
drivers and provides access to the native Linux UDP subsystem.
.PP
.B NPI-UDP
is implemented as a
.IR STREAMS (4)
pseudo-device driver and provides the following devices:
.TP
.IR /dev/np_udp ", " /dev/streams/np_udp ", " /dev/streams/clone/np_udp
This device provides access to the
.B NPI-UDP
protocol service interface using the N-primitives of the Network Provider Interface,
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
.BR npi (7),
used for the User Datagram Protocol as described in
.BR npi_udp (7).
The
.BR npi (7)
interface provided on a stream opening this device is suitable for use with
the
.BR sockets (3)
library and provides the
.B NPI-UDP
interface using sockets as described in
.BR npi_udp (7).
This stream provides connectionless, connection-oriented and multiplexed NPI services.
.TP
.IR /dev/udpcl ", " /dev/streams/np_udp/udpcl
This named minor device provides access to the
.B NPI-UDP
protocol service interface using the N-primitives of the Network Provider
Interface,
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
.BR npi (7),
used for the User Datagram Protocol as described in
.BR npi_udp (7).
The
.BR npi (7)
service interface provided on a Stream opening this device uses, by default,
a connectionless protocol.  This is the typical and default service interface
for
.B NPI-UDP
Streams.
.TP
.IR /dev/udpco ", " /dev/streams/np_udp/udpco
This device provides access to the
.B NPI-UDP
protocol service interface using the N-primitives of the Network Provider
Interface,
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
.BR npi (7),
used for the User Datagram Protocol as described in
.BR npi_udp (7).
The
.BR npi (7)
service interface provided on a Stream opening this device uses, by default,
a connection-oriented protocol.  This is an atypical service interface for
.B NPI-UDP
Streams, but has some specific use for symmetric UDP applications.
.RS
.PP
A pseudo-connection-oriented service interface is particularly useful for
symmetric, bidirectional UDP applications.  Symmetric, bidirectional UDP
applications are those that send from the same transport address for which
they receive and do not wish to receive packets from any remote transport
address other than the one to which they are connected.
An example of an application that can utilize pseudo-connection-oriented
service from UDP is the Real-Time Transport Protocol (RTP),
.[
rfc1889
.]
where it is being used in symmetric, bidirectional mode.
.[
bcp131
.]
.PP
A multi-homed pseudo-connection-oriented service interface is particularly
useful for multi-homed symmetric, bidirectional UDP applications.
Multi-homed applications are those that form connections between a local set
of IP addresses and a remote set of IP addresses, instead of simply between
two IP addresses, as in the single-homed case.
An example of an application that can utilize multi-homed
pseudo-connection-oriented service from UDP is the Stream Control Transport
Protocol (SCTP),
.[
rfc4960
.]
.BR sctp (4),
when run over UDP.
.RE
.TP
.IR /dev/udpmux ", " /dev/streams/np_udp/udpmux
This device provides access to the
.B NPI-UDP
protocol service interface using modified N-primitives of the Network
Provider Interface,
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
.BR npi (7),
used for the User Datagram Protocol as described in
.BR npi_udp (7).
The
.BR npi (7)
service interface provided on a Stream opening this device uses, by default,
a multiplexed protocol.  This is a specialized service interface that
provides for many UDP connectionless or connection-oriented instances on the
same Stream.  Each
.BR npi (7)
primitive is tagged with a connection identifier in a word prepended to the
primitive.
.RS
.PP
This device has particular use for large-scale access to the UDP subsystem,
where a multiplexing driver does not wish to link an individual UDP Stream
for each connection.  Instead, the device may link one NPI-UDP multiplexed
Stream and form as many individual and independent connections as desired.
The device supports both connectionless and pseudo-connection-oriented
operation, as well as multi-homing.
.RE
.\"
.\"
.SH USAGE
.PP
The following entries in
.B /etc/sock2path
provides the information necessary for
.BR socksys (4)
to use these devices:
.PP
.nf
\f(CW\s-1\
PF_INET     SOCK_RAW      IPPROTO_UDP   /dev/udpcl   npi   clts
PF_INET     SOCK_RAW      IPPROTO_UDP   /dev/udpco   npi   cots
\s+1\fP
.fi
.PP
For additional information, see
.BR socksys (4)
and
.BR sock2path (5).
.\"
.\"
.SH IOCTLS
.PP
All interfaces support a set of management IO controls using
.BR ioctl (2s)
and
.BR streamio (7)
.I I_STR
system calls on the
.IR udp_stream ", " udp_xtistr " or " udp_socket .
These management controls are described in
.BR udp_ioctl (4).
.\"
.\"
.SH NOTICES
.PP
.B NPI-UDP
has several implementations.  This manpage is for the
.IR STREAMS (4)
implementation.  There is also an
.BR INET (4)
implementation which provides
.BR tpi (7)
access to the Linux NET4 version of
.BR NPI-UDP .
For more information, see
.BR udp (7).
.PP
Note that using
.BR sockets (3)
over
.I STREAMS
for the
.B NPI-UDP
driver might be rather inefficient: unless you need to push modules, use a
direct Linux native socket instead.
.\"
.\"
.SH IMPLEMENTATION
.PP
The current
.B NPI-UDP
pseudo-device driver hook directly into the Linux kernel UDP subsystem.
Previous approaches used a STREAMS over Sockets method that was inefficient
and inflexible.
.\"
.\"
.\".SH EXAMPLES
.\".PP
.\"
.\"
.SH FILES
.PP
.BR <sys/socket.h> ,
.BR <netinet/ip.h> ,
.BR <netinet/udp.h> ,
.BR <sys/npi.h> ,
.BR <sys/npi_ip.h> ,
.BR <sys/tpi.h> ,
.BR <sys/tpi_ip.h> ,
.BR <sys/xti.h> ,
.BR <sys/xti_ip.h> .
.\"
.\"
.SH DEVICES
.PP
.IR /dev/np_udp ,
.IR /dev/rawip .
.\"
.\"
