.PP
.BR ioctl (2s),
.BR npi (7),
.BR npi_ip (7),
.BR npi_udp (7),
.BR sock2path (5),
.BR ip (7),
.BR ip (8),
.BR udp (7),
.BR udp_ioctl (4),
.BR socket (7),
.BR sockets (3),
.BR socksys (4),
.BR streamio (7),
.BR STREAMS (4),
.BR tpi (7),
.BR tpi_ip (7),
.BR tpi_udp (7),
.BR xnet (3),
.BR xti (3),
.BR xti_ip (3),
.BR xti_udp (3).
.\"
.\"
.SH BUGS
The
.B NPI-UDP
driver should be merged with the
.BR udp2 (4)
driver so that only one UDP hook is installed in the Linux IP system.
.\"
.\"
.SH COMPATIBILITY
.PP
The
.I /dev/rawip
device providing a Transport Provider Interface
.[
tpi revision 2.0.0 draft 2
.]
is roughly compatible with the raw udp TPI streams provided by
.IR Solaris \(rg
.[
soldoc
.]
and other
.IR UNIX \(rg
implementations.
.\"
.\"
.SH CONFORMANCE
.PP
While as consistent with the Network Provider Interface as possible, NPI
interfaces to UDP services are implementation dependent and are not subject
to standardization.
In particular, the multiplexed NPI interface is non-standard as is only
intended to solve problems associated with internal STREAMS interfaces
between modules and the Linux UDP subsystem.
.\"
.\"
.SH HISTORY
.PP
.I STREAMS
access to UDP services was originally performed using an STREAMS over Socket
approach using the
.BR INET (4)
pseudo-device driver from the
.I strinet
package.  A more flexible direct implementation was performed using a separate
driver that hooked directly into the Linux UDP subsystem, but initially only
provided the user-based Transport Provider Interface (TPI),
.[
tpi revision 2.0.0 draft 2
.]
.BR tpi (7),
interface.  This
Network Provider Interface (NPI),
.[
NPI Revision 2.0.0
.]
.BR npi (7),
interface was provided to
better support stacking protocol modules on top of the UDP driver.
